		<a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=9959'>No Burdens</a></font> <font class="afont">( was completely wrong )</font></TD></TR><TR><TD align='right' valign='top'><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"></td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top'><font class="bfont">This was an excellent article, but there were two points with which I must disagree.  First,<br>
you wrote that conditions were a problem almost exclusively to moria decks.  I must add<br>
that Sauron decks are also very condition heavy.  Under the Watching Eye and Orc Bowmen<br>
are two of the three most important cards in Sauron decks.  Sauron decks rely on the<br>
conditions to weaken the entire fellowship so that they can be picked off one by one with<br>
exertion wounds (hate, orc scouting band, etc).  Only when the fellowship has been<br>
sufficiently reduced by these conditions and wounds can the Sauron player begin to swarm.<br>
The other cultures have some very powerful conditions too (black breath, blade tip, worry,<br>
and Sauruman&#39;s ambition, to name a few) but Moria and Sauron decks are the more intensive.<br>
The second point of disagreement is with regards to deck discarding.  You claim that reducing<br>
the deck size will deny the shadow player minions, but this is not statistically true.  While<br>
it is true that, on average, the shadow player will have fewer total minions after having<br>
discarded cards from the top of his or her draw deck, it is not true that this will change the<br>
ratio between minions left in the deck and other cards.  Therefore, an average hand after<br>
reconcilliation will look the same no matter how many cards he or she just discarded, as<br>
long as there is still a draw deck left.  Most people play with more than sixty cards in a deck,<br>
even though they should not, so running out of cards usually will not happen (unless the<br>
deck is specifically designed to make it happen).  On a lighter note, concerning your last<br>
comment, the spelling and grammar in this article was much better than what a lot of other<br>
people post on here (even people who should know better, i.e. Americans).<br>
<br>
